  "text": "The global obesity epidemic and its associated complications have emphasized the importance of the adipose tissue as a regulator of metabolic function. Several hypotheses for the basis of the link between obesity and insulin resistance have proposed that an alteration in the adipokine profile, such as reduction of beneficial adipokines (for example, adiponectin) and increased secretion of proinflammatory adipokines (such as, TNF-a and resistin), contributes to the development of insulin resistance. [CITATION_1] Skeletal muscle is the principal target for postprandial insulin-stimulated glucose uptake, [CITATION_2] and our aim was to examine the effects of adipokine mixtures on glucose metabolism of skeletal muscle cells and the mechanisms mediating these effects. Although we must be cautious in extrapolating the effects observed in this direct coculture system to physiological relevance, where adiponectin is typically regarded as an endocrine hormone, it is important to note that recent literature supports the notion that adiponectin also mediates important functional autocrine effects. to the plasma membrane were measured in L6-GLUT4myc myoblasts. Values represent mean±s.e.m. fold increase in glucose uptake or GLUT4 content over control (Con), which was assigned a value of 1, and n ¼ 3, where *Po0.05 vs control. Insulin (100 nM) served as a positive control.",
